Comparative analysis of Metaheuristics Algorithms to solve Optimization Problems¶

1 Objective:¶

The purpose of this project is to explore and compare Metaheuristics Algorithms to solve Optimization Problems.

1.1 What is an optimization problem?¶

An optimization problem is defined by Russell and Norvig (2010) as a problem in which "the aim is to find the best state according to an objective function." [1] Optimization problems can be divided into two categories depending on whether the variables are continuous or discrete. An optimization problem with discrete variables is known as a discrete optimization. In a discrete optimization problem, we are looking for an object such as an integer, permutation or graph from a countable set. Problems with continuous variables include constrained problems and multimodal problems. [2]

For this study I have considered/modified three typical optimization problems which maximize the fitness function

  • Kanpsack Problem: Given a set of items, each with a weight and a value, determine the number of each item to include in a collection so that the total weight is less than or equal to a given limit and the total value is as large as possible. While the decision problem is NP-complete, the optimization problem is NP-hard. [3]
  • 8 Queens: In chess, the queen is the most powerful piece on the board. It can attack any piece in the same row, column or diagonal. In the 8-Queens problem, you are given a chessboard with eight queens (and no other pieces) and the aim is to place the queens on the board so that none of them can attack each other (Russell and Norvig (2010). This is a NP-Complete [4]
  • Travelling Sales Person(modified): The travelling salesperson problem (TSP) is a classic optimization problem where the goal is to determine the longest tour of a collection of n “cities” (i.e. nodes), starting and ending in the same city and visiting all of the other cities exactly once. In such a situation, a solution can be represented by a vector of n integers, each in the range 0 to n-1, specifying the order in which the cities should be visited. TSP is an NP-hard problem, meaning that, for larger values of n, it is not feasible to evaluate every possible problem solution within a reasonable period of time. Consequently, TSPs are well suited to solving using randomized optimization algorithms. [5]

1.2 Approaches to solve Optimization Problems¶

To solve the optimization problems, we a choice to implement Exact algorithms or Metaheuristic algorithms.
Exact algorithms consider entire solution spaces in order to give a global optima/minima whereas metaheuristic algorithms consider parts of the solution space and try to reach the best possible optima/minima.
For NP-hard problems, Exact algorithms take huge amount of computation time and hence it is not feasible to implement them. Metaheuristic algorithms are used when it's extremely difficult to an optimal solution due to model complexity or huge search space. These algorithms are also used when best possible sub-optimal solution is preferred in short amout of times.

Analysis is carried out on the following four Metaheuristic algorithms -

  • Random Hill Climbing: Algorithm iteratively does hill-climbing, each time with a random initial condition. The best condition is kept: if a new run of hill climbing produces a better condition than the stored state, it replaces the stored state. Random-restart hill climbing is a surprisingly effective algorithm in many cases. It turns out that it is often better to spend CPU time exploring the space, than carefully optimizing from an initial condition. [6]
  • Simulated Annealing: Algorithm uses probabilistic technique for approximating the global optimum of a given function. Specifically, it is a metaheuristic to approximate global optimization in a large search space for an optimization problem. It is often used when the search space is discrete [7]
  • Genetic Algorithm: Algorithm is inspired by the process of natural selection that belongs to the larger class of evolutionary algorithms (EA). Genetic algorithms are commonly used to generate high-quality solutions to optimization and search problems by relying on biologically inspired operators such as mutation, crossover and selection. [8]
  • MIMIC: Algorithm analyze the global structure of the optimization landscape. A novel and efficient algorithm for the estimation of the structure is derived. It uses knowledge of the structure to guide a randomized search through the solution space and, in turn, to refine our estimate of the structure. [9]

1.3 Libraries and Packages¶

This project uses mlrose library which implements some of the most common randomized optimization and search algorithms to a range of different optimization problems, over both discrete- and continuous-valued parameter spaces. Other standard packages are: numpy, pandas and matplotlib.
mlrose library is available at: https://github.com/hiive/mlrose/tree/master

2. Knapsack Problem¶

Number of objects: 20
Object Weights & Values: Weights of these 20 objects are generated randomly with uniform values between 1 and 15. Values of these 20 objects are generated randomly with uniform values between 10 and 1000.
Knapsack Capacity: Maximum capacity of the Knapsack is limited to 60%. This maximum capacity of knapsack (W) is defined as a percentage of the total of the weights list. (W = max_weight_pct x total_weight).

In [68]:
size=20
weights = np.random.uniform(low=1, high=15, size=size).astype('int')
values = np.random.uniform(low=10, high=1000, size=size).astype('int')
max_pct = 0.6

Fitness Function: Given a set of n items, where item i has known weight $w_{i}$ and known value $v_{i}$; and maximum knapsack capacity, W, the Knapsack fitness function evaluates the fitness of a state vector $x = [x_{0}, x_{1}, \ldots, x_{n-1}]$ as: \begin{equation*} Fitness(x) = \sum_{i = 0}^{n-1}v_{i}x_{i}, \text{ if} \sum_{i = 0}^{n-1}w_{i}x_{i} \leq W, \text{ and 0, otherwise,} \end{equation*} where $x_{i}$ denotes the number of copies of item i included in the knapsack. [10]

In [69]:
fitness = mlrose.Knapsack(weights, values, max_weight_pct=max_pct)
problem = mlrose.DiscreteOpt(length = size, fitness_fn = fitness, maximize = True, max_val = 2)

2.1 Step 1: Measure Fitness with Default Parameters and variable Max_Attempts¶

All four algorithms were executed with default values of their hyperparameters except max_attempts. Default Parameters for each algorithms are:

  • _random_hillclimb: max_iters=np.inf and restarts=0
  • _simulatedannealing: max_iters=np.inf and schedule=GeomDecay
  • _geneticalg: max_iters=np.inf, pop_size=200 and mutation_prob=0.1
  • mimic: np.inf, pop_size=200 and keep_pct=0.2
In [70]:
# Random Hill Climbing
algo_stats = []
for maxampts in range(10, 110, 40):
    t_start = time.time()*1000.0
    best_state, best_fitness, curve_vals = mlrose.random_hill_climb(problem,max_attempts=maxampts,curve=True,random_state=11)
    t_stop = time.time()*1000.0
    runtime = t_stop - t_start
    algo_stats.append(["Knapsack", "RHC", best_state, best_fitness, maxampts, curve_vals.size, curve_vals, runtime])  
    
# Genetic Algorithm
for maxampts in range(10, 110, 40):
    t_start = time.time()*1000.0
    best_state, best_fitness, curve_vals = mlrose.genetic_alg(problem, max_attempts=maxampts,curve=True,random_state=11)
    t_stop = time.time()*1000.0
    runtime = t_stop - t_start
    algo_stats.append(["Knapsack", "GA", best_state, best_fitness, maxampts, curve_vals.size, curve_vals, runtime]) 
    
# Simulated Annealing
for maxampts in range(10, 110, 40):
    t_start = time.time()*1000.0
    best_state, best_fitness, curve_vals = mlrose.simulated_annealing(problem,max_attempts=maxampts,curve=True,random_state=11)
    t_stop = time.time()*1000.0
    runtime = t_stop - t_start
    algo_stats.append(["Knapsack", "SA", best_state, best_fitness, maxampts, curve_vals.size, curve_vals, runtime]) 

# MIMIC
for maxampts in range(10, 110, 40):
    t_start = time.time()*1000.0
    best_state, best_fitness, curve_vals = mlrose.mimic(problem,max_attempts=maxampts,curve=True,random_state=11)
    t_stop = time.time()*1000.0
    runtime = t_stop - t_start
    algo_stats.append(["Knapsack", "MIMIC", best_state, best_fitness, maxampts, curve_vals.size, curve_vals, runtime])

2.2 Step 2: Hyper Parameter Tuning¶

Following hyperparameters were tuned for each algorithms:

  • _random_hillclimb: restarts
  • _simulatedannealing: schedule
  • _geneticalg: pop_size and mutation_prob
  • mimic: pop_size and keep_pct

Following hyperparameters were used based on the observations from step 1:

  • _random_hillclimb: max_attempts=50
  • _simulatedannealing: max_attempts=10
  • _geneticalg: max_attempts=50
  • mimic: max_attempts=10

# Simulated Annealing - Decay.

expdecay = mlrose.ExpDecay(init_temp=1.0, exp_const=0.005, min_temp=0.001)
arithdecay = mlrose.ArithDecay(init_temp=1.0, decay=0.0001, min_temp=0.001)
geomdecay = mlrose.GeomDecay(init_temp=1.0, decay=0.99, min_temp=0.001)

algo_stats = []
for decay in [expdecay, arithdecay, geomdecay]:
    t_start = time.time()*1000.0
    best_state, best_fitness, curve_vals = mlrose.simulated_annealing(problem,max_attempts=50,schedule=decay,curve=True,random_state=11)
    t_stop = time.time()*1000.0
    runtime = t_stop - t_start
    algo_stats.append(["Knapsack", "SA", best_state, best_fitness, type(decay).__name__, curve_vals.size, curve_vals, runtime])

Strength of Genetic Algorithms: The biggest benefit of Genetic Algorithm is the parallelism. This algorithm is less likely to stuck in the local optima because of the large number of instances in a search space. Genetic algorithm uses elitism to increase the selective pressure among the chromosomes which compete for survival across the search space. This approach ensurs global optima and high fitness level in the population.

Disadvantages of Genetic Algorithms: It may be difficult to select encoding and fitness function. Algorithm also has longer running time even on the smaller problems.

3 N Queens Problem¶

No of Queens: 8

In [133]:
size=8

Futness Function: Objective of the 8-Queens problem is to find a state vector for which all pairs of queens do not attack each other. In this context, we could define our fitness function as evaluating the number of pairs of non-attacking queens for a given state and try to maximize this function. [11]

In [134]:
# This function is copied from MLRose Tutorial
# https://mlrose.readthedocs.io/en/stable/source/tutorial1.html   
def queens_max(state):
    fitness_cnt = 0
    for i in range(len(state) - 1):
        for j in range(i + 1, len(state)):
            if (state[j] != state[i]) and (state[j] != state[i] + (j - i)) and (state[j] != state[i] - (j - i)):
                fitness_cnt += 1
    return fitness_cnt

fitness = mlrose.CustomFitness(queens_max)
In [135]:
fitness = mlrose.Queens()

init_state = np.array([0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0])

3.2 Step 2: Hyper Parameters Tuning¶

Following hyperparameters were tuned for each algorithms:

  • _random_hillclimb: restarts
  • _simulatedannealing: schedule
  • _geneticalg: pop_size and mutation_prob
  • mimic: pop_size and keep_pct

Following hyperparameters were used based on the observations from step 1:

  • _random_hillclimb: max_attempts=50
  • _simulatedannealing: max_attempts=10
  • _geneticalg: max_attempts=10
  • mimic: max_attempts=10

# Simulated Annealing - Decay.

expdecay = mlrose.ExpDecay(init_temp=1.0, exp_const=0.005, min_temp=0.001)
arithdecay = mlrose.ArithDecay(init_temp=1.0, decay=0.0001, min_temp=0.001)
geomdecay = mlrose.GeomDecay(init_temp=1.0, decay=0.99, min_temp=0.001)

algo_stats = []

    t_start = time.time()*1000.0
    best_state, best_fitness, curve_vals = mlrose.simulated_annealing(problem,max_attempts=10,schedule=decay,curve=True,random_state=11)

    runtime = t_stop - t_start
    algo_stats.append(["Knapsack", "SA", best_state, best_fitness, type(decay).__name__, curve_vals.size, curve_vals, runtime])

3.3 Step 3: Measure Fitness on Tuned Algorithms¶

In [181]:
# This function is copied from MLRose Tutorial
# https://mlrose.readthedocs.io/en/stable/source/tutorial1.html   
def queens_max(state):
    fitness_cnt = 0
    for i in range(len(state) - 1):
        for j in range(i + 1, len(state)):
            if (state[j] != state[i]) and (state[j] != state[i] + (j - i)) and (state[j] != state[i] - (j - i)):
                fitness_cnt += 1
    return fitness_cnt

fitness = mlrose.CustomFitness(queens_max)

Step 4 Observation: For the complex 50 Queen problem MIMIC perfromed much better than Genetic Algorithm with the best with highest fitness of 111.0. Runtime for MIMIC exponentially increased as comapred to Genetic Algorithm.

Comparision with perfromance in Step 3:
Perfromance of Genetic Algorithm decreased with increase in the complexity of the problem. Other trends such as runtime and iteration required to converge remained consistent.

Strength of MIMIC: MIMIC can discover underlying structure of problem very fast and converge quickly.Like Genetic Algorithm MIMIC evolves selection process by communicating information from one generation to next. In addition MIMIC leverages joint probability distribution in a chain-like model to represent successive dependencies between variables. MIMIC depends on the population size to generate the search space. For 8 Queens problem local optima is randomly uniformly distributed across the search space which explain the reason behind lower runtime of MIMIC as compared to that of Genetic Algorithm.

Disadvatanges of MIMIC: Algorithm takes long time to run and runtime increases exponentially with number of iterations it takes to converge.

4. Travelling Salesman Problem (modified)¶

Goal is to find the longest tour of the eight cities. As a result, the fitness function should calculate the total length of a given tour. Number of cities: 8

In [253]:
size=8
# Create list of city coordinates
coords_list = [(1, 1), (4, 2), (5, 2), (6, 4), (4, 4), (3, 6), (1, 5), (2, 3)]

Fitness Function: Fitness function for Travelling Salesman optimization problem. Evaluates the fitness of a tour of n nodes, represented by state vector x, giving the order in which the nodes are visited, as the total distance travelled on the tour (including the distance travelled between the final node in the state vector and the first node in the state vector during the return leg of the tour). Each node must be visited exactly once for a tour to be considered valid. [12]

In [254]:
# Initialize fitness function object using coords_list

Comparision with perfromance in Step 1:
Fitness of Genetic Algorithm and MIMIC improved slightly with the algorithm tunning whereas it remained same for Random Hill Climbing and Simulated Annealing. After perfrmance tuning, Genetic Algorithm converged much quickly which also reduced the runtime.

Step 4 Observation: For the complex 40 cities TSP problem Simulated Annealing perfromed much better than MIMIC with the best with highest fitness of 403.58. Runtime for Simulated Annealing also increased proportionally as comapred to exponentially increased of runtime for MIMIC Genetic Algorithm.

Comparision with perfromance in Step 2: Perfromance of Simulated Annealing increased with increase in the complexity of the problem. Other trends such as runtime and iteration required to converge remained consistent.

Strength of Simulated Annealing: Travelling salesman problem is a NP-Hard problem and the fitness landscape of the choosen problem has many local optima. Although Simulated Annealing is greedy algorithm unlike Random Hill Climbing it accepts worse solutions by slowly decreasing the probability of accepting such bad solutions in search space. If the search space is large it find the global optima. In this choosen problem Simulated Annealing performed as good as MIMIC and Genetic Algorithm because of its ability to get out of local optima by randomizing search space. Simulated annealing is extremely fast as compared Genetic Algorithm and MIMIC.

Weakness of Simulated Annealing: If the underlying structure is complex, Simulated Annealing may get stuck in the local optima. As it accepts worst solutions when temperature is high, we might see poor convergance rate.
